ce:section.ce:para:
Laser ablation, chemical/electrochemical oxidation, ultrasonic, and arc discharge methods are widely used among various top-down approaches. In the laser ablation method, a dense carbon-based material is exposed to a highly energetic laser beam, leading to extremely high temperatures and pressures. This process induces heating and plasma formation, followed by crystallization that converts the resulting vapor into carbon-based QDs (Fig. 2
                           ) [47]. Chemical/electrochemical oxidation synthesizes QDs by applying a voltage to a bulk carbon electrode in an electrolyte solution (Fig. 3
                           a), breaking it down into nanoscale QDs with oxygen-rich functional groups [48,49]. The ultrasonic method uses bulk graphite or carbon nanotubes (CNTs) to undergo disintegration through ultrasound waves in a liquid medium, generating powerful hydrodynamic shear forces (Fig. 3) [49–51]. The arc discharge method generates a high-temperature plasma between two carbon electrodes, causing the carbon to vaporize and condense into nanoscale particles in a controlled gas or liquid environment [52].
